o), and verify findings appear in their correct sections with proper formatting.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A pull request that touches 200 files completes analysis within the 10-minute Actions timeout","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Performance is non-deterministic and depends on real I/O, subprocess overhead, and analysis time. Mocks would hide performance bottlenecks—a mocked file-read and mocked analyzer are instant, so tests would always pass even if real execution times out. The real failure boundary is actual elapsed time with realistic file sizes and count. This requires System-level testing with real or realistic-scale test data and actual analysis tools.","test_description":"Create or generate a test directory with 200 real files of realistic size and complexity. Run the linter step in a CI environment (or Docker container simulating CI), measuring total elapsed time from start to finish of all file I/O and analysis. Verify the entire process (including file reading, analysis, grouping, and comment generation) completes in under 10 minutes. Verify all 200 files are analyzed.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the linter process crashes on a malformed file, the remaining files are still analyzed and results posted","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The real failure is: the process crashes, and remaining files are NOT analyzed. This can be tested at Integration level by mocking the linter to raise an exception or return a failure code on one file, then verifying that the error is caught, processing continues, and remaining files are analyzed with partial results posted. System-level testing with a real linter crashing on malformed input would be more thorough but isn't required for the error-